Another 100 finish. Decided to bag the 24hr and do the 100 miler. The track ultra is a different sport! You need a lot of adaptations to flat, repetitive running muscles. Probably didn’t help that the Moab 240 effort was 9 weeks before😳 My longest track run was 21 miles. It was awesome to see @runcamille in her element — she’s a machine! 😤🤯 So many impressive performances from these crazy people. 🔥 The track loops — uh, little insane! 😵‍💫 Back to trails for this old mountain 🐐! Awesome event, great new friends. Very social. I’ll be back…hanging out and spectating! 🤣😎🤙🏼

Coldwater Rumble 100 is a deceptively hard course. Lots of halfpipe-like washes — some little, some gigantic. Never felt like I hiked more than 5-30 meters at a time. Rocky, roller traverses, soft sandy sections, and low-grade passes. Tons of grindy running.🌵

Funky, cool loop with a washing-machine-style format. Trail is wide in most places, so it’s easy to meet and pass people. Social and fun to see who and where runners are behind you. 

27th 100-mile win, 47th hundred finish. Giddyup! 🤙🏼

A quick interruption in Jeff’s running stream to wish this guy the happiest Father’s Day. (Jeff, you should think twice before giving me access to your account.) While we’re ever impressed with your trail-running accomplishments (Bighorn makes 100-mile-win #29), that’s not why we love you. You have spent the past 21 years of fatherhood giving yourself every day to these kids in all the ways that matter. A thousand sword fights and countless bedtime stories later, the love we feel for you is best expressed in the way our youngest child looked at you before #bighorn100 on Friday morning. Happy Father’s Day to our absolute favorite. Oh, and giddyup! —Love,  Jennifer, Ben, Annie & Abe

In 2005 I secured my first 100-mile win at #Bighorn100. I returned in 2006, 2008 & 2010. Looking back, I see Bighorn is where I really learned to race. So it was sweet to return this year, a long 13 years after my last showing. The race was bigger, but it retains all of that small-town charm and down-to-earth personality that made me fall in love with ultrarunning culture to begin with. The course is primitive and wild, and I was quickly reminded why it’s known in some circles as Little Hardrock. Thanks to the the entire Bighorn staff for a well-run race and hospitality that seems hard to come by these days. They literally gave my son and I the Bighorn 100 hats from their heads. As for this year’s race, it isn’t often that a 100-miler comes down to the final seconds. Seth Swanson and David Ayala threw down for a full 100 miles. It was everything I could have asked for my 49th hundred and a perfect way to kick off the #rockymountainslam. Giddyup! Photo by @derricklytle

The legendary Roch Horton told me about the #RockyMountainSlam when we shared a campsite at my first #Bighorn100 in 2005. I immediately wanted to do it. But having run only a handful of 100s at the time, running four difficult Rocky Mountain 100-milers in one summer seemed insane. Not so much 18 years later. When planning my season, my wife suggested I run six hundreds to bring my total of 100s run up to my total of years lived (52 in August). I knocked out two 100s this spring before the RMS kicked off. As of this year, the Rocky Mountain Slam (RMS) has evolved to become the RMS 2.0. There have been new races added to the RMS list due to Hardrock’s difficulty of entry. My picks: Bighorn 100, Hardrock 100, Wasatch 100, and Bear 100. One down, three to go! Giddyup!

My first #Hardrock100 was in 2007.  I had two young kids, and Abraham (pictured) was still four years away from coming into this world like a whirlwind. That year, Hardrock was my fifth hundred miler and proved to be a learning experience. It’s still my slowest 100 miler at 33:18. 

I went out hard and slept at Chapman aid station for 45 minutes in order to get myself straight and able to finish. 

Fast forward 16 years: What a joy to have this little man waiting on the edge of town to run in with me. Hardrock is truly one of a kind. It’s still wild and tough, I’m just a little more seasoned and possibly wiser than the 2007 version of myself. 🤔🤣

Stoked to have the 50+ age group fastest times in both directions now, as well as the nice career stat of 50 hundred mile finishes. Crazy how time flies. Giddyup! 🔥

Are carbs the best source of fuel for endurance performance?

Today’s episode dives DEEP into all things nutrition for optimal health and performance with @gobroncobilly !

Jeff Browning, A.K.A “Bronco Billy” is an endurance coach, ultra-athlete, designer, husband, and father of three kids. He has finished nearly 200 ultra marathons in his career, racking up over 40 career ultra wins — 28 of those at the 100-mile plus distance, making him 2nd in the world for the most 100-mile wins in history.

In this conversation, Jeff provides valuable insights on improving as a runner, emphasizing essential principles to help runners of all levels reach their goals. 

Jeff sheds light on the concept of oxidative fat metabolism and its significance for endurance athletes. Strategies to optimize the body’s ability to burn fat for fuel are explored, as well as insights on nutrition timing and fueling for both health and peak performance.

🔗Watch or listen at the link in my bio!

Sit and kick to finish a 100. Out of 51 finishes, that’s a first! 

It was a Wasatch podium throw down (2nd and 3rd). Jon Love caught me with approximately 18 miles to go and I surged. He caught me again 3.5 miles from the finish line. “Good job, dude,” I said. We proceeded to run shoulder to shoulder (without another word between us) at a strong pace the last 5K on the lakeshore gravel pathway, and picked it up the last half mile. High school track muscle memory is strong and I out-kicked Jon by 2 seconds, to which he responded: “That’s how I expected it to play out.” Thanks, Jon, for the pressure. 🔥👊🏼What a unique 100 finish. My HS 800 strategy — sit and kick! Giddyup. 

And congratulations to Jose on the win. Tried multiple times before dark to reel him in. Strong work! 💪🏼

Photo cred / @keston_moore / The Juniper Lab

#R2R2R alt route: Old B.A. trail to North Rim. It was the original trail from North Rim, but has been unmaintained since North Kaibab’s construction. It was tough; a proper bushwhacking adventure. My arms and legs look like I got in a fight with a wildcat. 🩸

Safety Note: On the climb out of South Kaibab after dark, we helped a girl who had no light and a dead phone. By the time we found her, she was hours without food and water, dehydrated and scared. I’m so grateful we were in the right place at the right time. A good reminder: Never underestimate the power of the #GrandCanyon
